bug.short_desc: Compiler chokes on funny character in source file

long_desc.thetext: *** Bug 1926 has been marked as a duplicate of this bug. ***

The scenario seems to be rare, but not unlikely on a Mac system: Alt+Space seems to introduce such a non-breaking space (?) independent of the editor used.
"generate.py fix" could be a tool to remove such unwanted whitespaces. But how to handle the regular build process: bark or automagic?

see bug #1662 for handling the byte-order mark (BOM) in Unicode files. Explicit handling (removal) seems to be fine in "fix" target. As Thomas said, the tokenizer should bark on such potentially dangerous characters as well.
Untarget 0.8.2

Well, barking may not really be ok, given that there are quite some whitespaces that are allowed per ECMAScript spec (thanks to Martin for digging this up, see attachment). The toolchain should be able to properly work with those specified whitespaces...
Created attachment 452 ECMAScript spec for whitespaces

I want to point out at this point that the disturbing byte encountered in the source code (0xC2) is on first sight *not* a legal unicode white space character. It might be a white space *code point*, but in utf-8 encoding (which is our standard) this code point would be encoded in probably 2 octets, not just one. On the other hand, in utf-8 0xC2 *has* to be part of a 2 octet utf-8 value, which seems not be true in our examples. That means, if I'm right the 0xC2 octet effectively *devalidates* the utf-8 encoding of the file, rendering its encoding corrupt.
Created attachment 454 Added a framework interface with such a character included.
It turns out that a legal Utf-8 character was inserted (C2 A0), which is supposed to be a unicode white space character (code point A0). This is now parsed correctly as white space (with r18080).
mass correction: set previously unspecified target milestone to 0.8.2

I've added a filter for "generate fix". It basically does
content.replace(ur"\u00A0", " ")
Note that using ur"\uFEFFF" like in our JavaScript parser does not work. Wee should check if this code in the generator is correct.

The re-opening of the bug was not due to a defect in the tool chain, but rather to help a community member that was struggling with legal unicode space characters in qooxdoo source code. As we don't rely on them, we could also replace them with the ASCII space character, which Fabian did in the 'fix' job.
The code in the parser should be fine as is, as it matches against any kind of unicode white space which includes 0x00A0 and the other chars from the category 'Zs', so no changes here.
I generalized the "generate fix" job to replace all unicode separator space chars (category 'Zs').
A general issue with these kind of generalisation is that Python's regex don't support unicode properties (like Perl's "\p{Zs}"), so you have to roll your own character classes to represent these properties.
With r20877.
Closed all bugs already shipped with a release.
